\pard\plain \s1\qj \f18\fs28 Darkscreen\tab {\f13 s}\par 
\pard\plain \qj \f16\fs20 Discipline/Level: Illusion 1 Spell\par 
Preparation: None\par 
Magick Points: 3\par 
Range: BMP yards\par 
Duration: 1d6+3 rounds\par 
Area of Effect: 4-by-2-yard screen\par 
Ingredients: Air sublimates*, lampblack\par 
Resistance: None\par 
\par 
\tab Rationale: Air nodes form a thin, rigid, sheet-like opaque frame made opaque by particles of lampblack in suspension. The nodes forming this opaque screen move at the caster\rquote s command.\par 
\tab Magick Effects: This magickal black screen obscures vision from both sides. The four-yard-wide, two-yard-high opaque screen may be moved instantaneously within the caster\rquote 
s control range at the beginning of each round (i.e., no part of the screen may extend farther than the caster\rquote s BMP). WS and BS are hal
ved for melee and missile attacks and parries by characters on opposite sides of the screen. Casting magick missiles at targets obscured by this screen requires a successful BS test.\par 
{\*\bkmkstart LINK2}\tab A caster may perform no other action than moving at a Cautious rate during the duration of effect. If interrupted, the spell effect ends. A caster may not maintain more than one of the following spells at the same time: {\i 
darkscreen}, {\i lightscreen}. Subsequent casting of one of these spells immediately interrupts the previously cast spell.\par 
{\*\bkmkend LINK2}\tab Notes: The BS test for casting magick missiles through a Darkscreen reflects the caster\rquote s chance to guess the location of his target.\par 
\tab Variants: {\i Lightscreen} and {\i colorscreen} (Illusion 2). {\i Colorscreen} is identical to {\i darkscreen}, except that the scr
een is a chaotic swirl of colors, and requires an expensive pallet of powdery pigmented glass glazes. At this mastery level, colors and forms of the colors are not controllable by the caster. {\i Colorscreen}
 is often used as a backdrop to enhance dramatic, musical, and visual performances.\par 
\par 
