}\pard\plain \s1\qj \f18\fs28 Stampede\par 
\pard\plain \qj \f16\fs20 Discipline/Level: Illusion 2 Spell\par 
Preparation: None\par 
Magick Points: 4\par 
Range: BMP yards\par 
Duration: 1d6+3 turns\par 
Area of Effect: Herd animals in 10 yard radius sphere\par 
Reagents: Chaotic magickal creature extracts*, air sublimates*\par 
Resistance: WP\par 
\par 
\tab Rationale: The scent of the creature the extracts are from is delivered to the target animals via air nodes, causing them to panic and stampede.\par 
\tab 
Magick Effects: A group of natural animals is excited into a state of panic, causing them to stampede. Affected creatures are forced to flee uncontrollably in a direction chosen at time of casting,  at their maximum movement rate.  If an affected animal i
s acting as a mount, and the rider has the appropriate Ride skill, he is permitted a Ld test each turn after the first to bring the animal under control , with a +10 bonus for the following skills: Trick Riding, Animal Trainer (if mount trained
 by its rider).\par 
\tab While the creatures are only forced to stampede for the duration of the spell, they tend to associate the caster as the cause of their fear, and will resist approaching him for 24 to 48 hours.\par 
\tab This spell does not affect mounts immune to psychological effects, nor does it affect creatures such as chaos steeds appearing as animals, since these are not natural creatures.\par 
\par 
\par 
\pard\plain \s1\qj \f18\fs28 Suggestion\par 
\pard\plain \qj \f16\fs20 Discipline/Level: Illusion 2 Ritual\par 
Preparation: 1d6+3 rounds\par 
Magick Points: 4\par 
Range: BMP yards\par 
Duration: Indefinite\par 
Area of Effect: One victim\par 
Reagents: Deleriants (1/20 dose)\par 
Resistance: WP/hour\par 
\par 
\tab Rationale: The caster introduces to the victim\rquote s mind one idea about a recent event, experience, or piece of information. The idea may be true, false, or misleading. The victim\rquote 
s mind is then compelled to accept the idea as an idea of his own.\par 
\tab Magick Effects: An idea expressed by the caster in ten words or fewer is planted in the victim\rquote s mind, and accepted by the victim as accurate and genuine. Each hour (or more frequently, at the GM\rquote 
s discretion) the victim tests vs. WP to resist the magick effect. If successful, the victim realizes the implanted idea is not his own, and is no longer magickally misled.\par 
\tab 
Background: Ancient High Elven. Though the magick effect itself is reliable and well-understood, the personal beliefs and mental abilities of the victims vary widely, and the implanted ideas vary in complexity and plausibility, so the duration and results
 are somewhat unpredictable.\par 
\tab Notes: Under magickal compulsion, the victim\rquote s mind tries to shape the introduced idea so it appears to fit with the victim\rquote s other ideas and personal beliefs. The more appropriate the introduced idea to the victim\rquote 
s own ideas and personal beliefs, the more likely is the victim to accept it as genuinely his own.\par 
\tab A WP test per hour is the minimum; the GM may judge that more frequent tests are appropriate, particularly if the implanted idea is challenged by experience or by cross-examination by others. For example, if an orc is given the idea
 that his boar-boyz-buddies is gone home, contrary evidence (like running into his buddies) or contrary testimony (an orc leader of another unit tells him that none of the boyz is gone home), the victim may be entitled to an immediate WP test.\par 
\tab Exceptionally plausible ideas that fit neatly with the victim\rquote s personal beliefs, or exceptionally implausible ideas that don\rquote t fit at all with victim\rquote s personal beliefs, may require that the GM assess modifiers to each WP test.
\par 
\tab For example, an orc is told that he has single-handedly wiped out the PC party he was sent to find. \ldblquote Orcs is great!\rdblquote  and the orc {\b wants} to think he\rquote 
s a hero, so the WP test might be at -10 or -20 penalty. On the other hand, a smart PC wizard is told by a nasty villain wizard that his buddies have abandoned him. The smart PC wizard knows his buddies have been with him for years, and would 
never abandon him, and furthermore, the smart PC wizard is smart enough to distrust odd ideas that might have been slipped into his mind magickally, so a +10 or +20 bonus to the WP test might be appropriate.\par 
\par 
\par 
{\v David Peterson, was Battle spell\par 
