\pard\plain \s4\qc \f18\fs36 Illusionist 3rd Castings\par 
\pard\plain \s1\qj \f18\fs28 \par 
\par 
Dream Sending\par 
\pard\plain \qj \f16\fs20 Discipline/Level: Illusion 3 Ritual\par 
Preparation: 1d6+3 rounds\par 
Magick Points: 6\par 
Range: BMP yds\par 
Duration: 2d6+6 rounds\par 
Area of Effect: One subject\par 
Ingredients: Deleriants (1 dose)\par 
Resistance: WP\par 
\par 
\tab Rationale: The caster prepares a dream sequence illusion in his own mind, then enters into the mind of the subject and implants that dream sequence within the subject's imagination.\par 
\tab Magick Effects: If the subject is asleep during the spell effect, the subject has the dream immediately. If the subject is awake, the subject has the dream the next time he falls asleep.\par 
\tab The dream actually only lasts for 2d6+6 rounds, but from the subject\rquote s perspective, the duration of the dream may seem much longer.\par 
\tab The subject may unconsciously attempt to resist the dream sending. Test vs. WP to resist. A successful test means the subject remains asleep and dreaming, but is aware that he\rquote 
s having a dream. The subject may then choose to wake up and interrupt the drea
m, or continue to observe the dream in a conscious manner. A failed test means the subject remembers the dream after he awakes, and is convinced that the dream is his own, and that it has some deep significance.\par 
\tab Notes: In combination with the {\i voidsend mind} ritual, the dream may be sent to a subject within range of a caster\rquote s remote focus, which might easily be hidden in the subject's sleeping quarters.\par 
\tab At the gamemaster\rquote 
s option, if the dream sending is nightmarish and horrific, he may give the subject an Insanity Point unless the subject makes a Cool test to resist. Repeated nightmares have diminished effect, however. A subject should receive no more t
han a maximum of 6 Insanity Points as a direct result of Dream Sendings.\par 
\tab Other possible effects of dreams will vary according to the subject and the circumstances, and must be judged by the GM at his discretion. For example:\par 
\tab \bullet  In a dream, the subject is attacked by an assassin. If a dagger is close to hand, the subject may suffer from a self-inflicted wound unless he makes a WP test.\par 
\tab \bullet  The subject receives a series of bogus divine visions. The subject must test vs. WP or become deeply disturbed and obsessed by these visions. The subject may
 or may not be convinced that these divine visions are genuine, but if he does not believe them genuine, he may suspect some malign force within himself of producing the visions.\par 
\tab \bullet 
 The subject receives a series of dreams featuring horrible atrocities performed by elves. Each time he receives such a dream, he tests vs. WP or gains 1 point of Elf Obsession. When he accumulates 10 points of Elf Obsession, he gains a Hatred of Elves.
\par 
\tab Against ignorant, unsophisticated, or mentally unstable subjects, this magic
k effect should be a dangerous and effective weapon. Against experienced spellcasters, adventurers, and other tough-minded characters, this should be less effective, with bonuses to tests to resist.\par 
\tab Note that someone who suspects himself a target of dream sendings can protect himself, and convince himself that the sendings are sorcerous attacks, by isolating himself from possible contact with sorcerors, and by {\i detect magick}
 searches of his sleeping quarters for remote focuses.\par 
\par 
