\par 
\tab Rationale: The caster establishes a link with the victim\rquote s mind (similar to the {\i read vision} ritual). Then the caster gradually alters elements in the victim\rquote s perceptions to produce a plausible illusion in the victim\rquote 
s mind. Since the caster enlists the victim\rquote s other senses as well as vision to reinforce the illusion, the image is very persuasive.\par 
\tab Magick Effects: The victim tests vs. WP to resist the magick effect. If successful, the victim subconsciously resists the effects of the ritual but is not conscious of the mental intrusion. If the test fails, the victim is affected by the ritual.
\par 
\tab Each round the caster may alter the victim\rquote s perception of one element of his surroundings. The element to be altered and the alteration to be made are stated as a simple sentence (e.g., \ldblquote The door appears to open\rdblquote , 
\ldblquote The prisoner appears to move into the cell\rdblquote , etc.). The caster must monitor the victim\rquote s perceptions throughout the duration of the ritual, and cannot perform any other action without interrupting the spell effects.\par 
\tab If the altered element is judged by the GM to be plausible to the victim, the victim receives no further test vs. WP to resist. (\ldblquote The notebook that Dieter stole appears to still be lying on the desk.\rdblquote )\par 
\tab If the altered element is judged by the GM to be somewhat implausible, the victim receives an immediate test vs. WP to resist. (\ldblquote A daemon appears in the lower branches of the oak tree.\rdblquote  \ldblquote 
An orc appears suddenly from behind the wardrobe and attacks you.\rdblquote )\par 
\tab If the altered element is judged by the GM to be completely implausible, the victim receives an immediate test vs. WP to resist, with appropriate GM modifiers, or an automatically successful test to resist, at the GM\rquote s option. (\ldblquote 
A dozen orcs appear suddenly from within the wardrobe and attack you.\rdblquote  \ldblquote The mage gestures, and the city outside the window falls upward into the sky.\rdblquote )\par 
\tab Notes: In a world where sorcerors, divine spellcasters, aethyrial beings, and gods are commonplace knowledge, many events that would otherwise seem implausible might be interpreted as plausible if a magickal agency were involved.\par 
\tab Projected images have no affect whatsoever on the real world. However, since a project image includes the sense of touch, including pain from imagined injuries, a victim may think himself physically affected as by a real event. Further, sinc
e injuries in combat are especially plausible in many circumstances, the victim is unlikely to receive a test vs. WP to resist.\par 
\tab For example, a victim may be told that an arrow strikes him. At the caster\rquote 
s option, he may choose to have the victim feels as though he were slightly wounded, seriously wounded, or even as affected by the Critical Hit Effects table. For the duration of t
he spell effect, the victim is more or less likely to believe he has indeed suffered an injury, depending on his Toughness and armor and the illusory attack form. Of course, if the illusionary injury is implausible according to the circumstances (
\ldblquote The snotling drives his dagger through your shield and plate mail, delivering a critical hit to your chest.\rdblquote ), the victim deserves a test vs. WP to resist the illusion.\par 
\tab Judging the effects of this ritual require the improvisational genius and good graces of both the GM and the player. In general, the more simple and subtle the projected illusion, the more likely it is to be persuasive, wh
ile the more gross and dramatic the illusion, the less likely the victim will be persuaded. Really stupid, ignorant, and superstitious victims are easily flummoxed, while sophisticated, experienced sorcerors, adventurers, and tough-minded skeptics are goin
g to be tough to fool. If this means the PCs can abuse dopey NPCs at will, while NPC villains have a hard time suckering PCs, so be it.\par 
