\pard\plain \s1\qj \f18\fs28 Projected Illusion Sequence\par 
\pard\plain \qj \f16\fs20 Discipline/Level: Illusion 4 Spell\par 
Preparation: None\par 
Magick Points: 6\par 
Range: BMP yards\par 
Duration: 1d6+3 rounds\par 
Area of Effect: One victim\par 
Ingredients: Deleriants (1 dose)\par 
Resistance: WP\par 
\par 
\tab Rationale: The caster establishes a link with the victim\rquote s mind (similar to the {\i read vision} ritual), then projects a sequence of altered elements in the victim\rquote s perceptions to produce a plausible illusion in the victim\rquote 
s mind. Since the caster enlists the victim\rquote s other senses as well as vision to reinforce the illusion, the image is very persuasive.\par 
\tab Magick Effects: The victim tests vs. WP to resist the magick effect. If successful, the victim subconsciously resists the effects of the spell but is not conscious of the mental intrusion. If the test fails, the spell takes effect.\par 
\tab In the successive rounds of the spell\rquote s effect, a series of elements are altered in the victim\rquote 
s perception. When the spell is cast, the caster specifies which elements are to be altered, how they are to be altered, and in what sequence. The player must l
ist the elements to be altered in each round, with a brief description of how they are to be altered (see Notes below for an example).\par 
\tab Once the spell is cast, the caster need no longer supervise the spell, and may perform other actions without penalty.\par 
\tab Otherwise, this spell\rquote s effects are identical to those of the {\i project illusion} ritual (Illusionist 3). See that description for details.\par 
\tab Notes: This spell will permit a caster to project illusions upon a number of victims in successive rounds, or to project a programmed sequence of illusory events upon a victim, leaving the caster free for other actions.\par 
\tab When the spell is cast, the player should note down 
the sequence of illusions the victim experiences, or describe the sequence of illusions to the GM. The more detailed the notes and description, the more satisfying the illusion, but remember: this is a spell that is cast in a few seconds, and only a limite
d amount of detail should be possible. Either notes or description should take no longer than one or two minutes, or the GM may judge that the spell is delayed until a following round.\par 
\tab Here\rquote s an example of notes on the sequence of illusions:\par 
\tab \bullet  Round 1, the side door opens.\par 
\tab \bullet  Round 2, two armored Dark Elves revealed by the opening door fire their bows at our evil enemies, missing their targets (of course, since they\rquote re illusory arrows).\par 
\tab \bullet  Round 3, a Dark Elf Lord with a glowing runesword appears in the door as the two armored Dark Elves withdraw, and behind the Dark Elf Lord is a Necromancer pointing his staff and mumbling.\par 
\tab \bullet  Round 4, a wall of darkness forms in front of our enemies, and a shrill keening sound like a soul in torment washes over our enemies.\par 
\tab \bullet  Rounds 5-8, same as round 4.\par 
